.TH SLAG 1 "2026-07-03" "slag 0.13" "Slag Programming Language"
.SH NAME
slag \- compile Slag source files to native Win64 PE executables
.SH SYNOPSIS
.B slag
.I file.slag
.SH DESCRIPTION
.B Slag
is a statically typed, compiled systems programming language that targets
native Win64 PE executables. The compiler translates
.I .slag
source files directly into NASM x86-64 assembly for the
.B win64
object format. Compiled programs link against no C runtime; only
.BR kernel32.dll ,
.BR user32.dll ,
and
.B gdi32.dll
are imported, and only as needed by the features a given program uses.
.PP
Running
.B slag
on a source file produces a
.I .asm
file of the same base name. This must be assembled with NASM and linked
with a Win64-capable linker (such as the MinGW-w64 GCC driver) to produce
a runnable
.I .exe
file. See
.B EXAMPLES
below for the full pipeline.
.SH LANGUAGE OVERVIEW
.SS Source files
Slag source files use the
.B .slag
extension. A program is a sequence of top-level function declarations.
Execution begins at
.B main()
if one is defined; otherwise execution begins at the first function
declared in the file.
.SS Types
.TP
.B int
64-bit signed integer.
.TP
.B float
64-bit IEEE double. Mixed int/float expressions are promoted
automatically (int operands are converted via
.BR cvtsi2sd );
assigning a float expression to an
.B int
truncates via
.BR cvttsd2si .
No explicit cast syntax exists or is required.
.TP
.B str
A string value, internally represented as a pointer/length pair.
String literals are double-quoted and support
.BR \en ,
.BR \et ,
.BR \e\e ,
.BR \e" ,
and
.B \e0
escapes.
.TP
.B bool
Boolean value,
.B true
or
.BR false .
.TP
.B void
Used only as a function's declared return type for functions that
return no value.
.SS Variables and arrays
Every variable is declared with an explicit scope modifier,
.B global
or
.BR local ;
there is no unscoped declaration form:
.PP
.RS
.nf
local int x = 5;
local float f = 3.14;
local str  s = "hello";
local int[5] nums = {10, 20, 30, 40, 50};
.fi
.RE
.PP
Arrays are fixed-size and 1-dimensional. Indexing uses
.BR arr[i] ,
and the element count is available via
.BR arr.len .
.SS Variable scope
.TP
.B global
Declares a file-scope variable stored in the .data section, accessible
from any function:
.PP
.RS
.nf
global int counter = 0;
global str appName = "MyApp";
.fi
.RE
.TP
.B local
Declares a block-scoped, stack-allocated variable:
.PP
.RS
.nf
local int x = 10;
.fi
.RE
.SS Arithmetic expressions
Arithmetic operators work directly on expressions, with no wrapper
syntax or variable sigil required. The same plain expression syntax
is used everywhere, including
.B if
and
.B while
conditions:
.PP
.RS
.nf
i = i + 1;
total = total + nums[j];
while (i < nums.len) { ... }
.fi
.RE
.SS Control flow
.B if
/
.B else
(including chained
.BR "else if" )
and
.B while
are supported. There is no
.B for
loop.
.SS Functions
Functions are declared with the
.B function
keyword. Parameters are typed; the return type is declared at the
.B return
statement itself rather than in the function signature:
.PP
.RS
.nf
function add(int a, int b) {
    return int a + b;
}
function greet(str name) {
    println(name);
    return;
}
.fi
.RE
.SH BUILT\-IN FUNCTIONS
.SS I/O
.TP
.BI print( expr )
Print a value (int, float, or str) to standard output with no trailing
newline.
.TP
.BI println( expr )
Print a value (int, float, or str) to standard output followed by a
trailing newline.
.TP
.BI readline()
Read a line of input from standard input. Returns a
.BR str .
.TP
.BI readfile( path )
Read the entire contents of the file at
.I path
into a
.BR str .
.SS Windowing and graphics
.TP
.BI window.open( width , " height" , " title" )
Create a window of the given dimensions and title, with a BGRA pixel
framebuffer, running on its own thread. Window state is stored in
thread-local storage (TLS), so multiple threads can each open their
own independent window.
.TP
.B window.close()
Request that the open window close.
.TP
.B window.is_open()
Returns 1 if the window is still open, 0 otherwise. Intended for use
as a main-loop condition.
.TP
.B window.flush()
Pump the window's message queue and blit the current framebuffer
contents to the screen. Caps the frame rate to approximately 60 FPS.
.TP
.B window.capture_mouse()
Capture the mouse, clip the cursor to the window bounds, and hide the
cursor. Useful for FPS-style controls.
.TP
.B window.release_mouse()
Release mouse capture and show the cursor.
.TP
.B window.native()
Returns the native screen resolution as a string in "WxH" format
(e.g., "1920x1080").
.TP
.BI window.clear( r , " g" , " b" )
Fill the entire DIB framebuffer with a solid color via a single
.B rep stosd
fill. Typically called once per frame before drawing.
.TP
.BI window.text( x , " y" , " value" , " r" , " g" , " b" )
Draw
.I value
(a
.B str
or
.BR int )
as text at
.RI ( x , " y" )
via GDI
.BR TextOutA ,
composited into the same DIB surface that
.B window.flush()
blits.
.TP
.BI pixel( x , " y" , " r" , " g" , " b" )
Write a single RGB pixel into the framebuffer at
.RI ( x , " y" ).
Out-of-bounds coordinates are silently ignored.
.PP
All
.B fill_triangle*
variants below perform backface culling: a signed-area winding test
discards triangles whose vertices are not in clockwise (CW) order.
.TP
.BI fill_triangle( x0 , " y0" , " x1" , " y1" , " x2" , " y2" , " r" , " g" , " b" )
Rasterize a flat-shaded, solid-color triangle directly into the
framebuffer.
.TP
.BI fill_triangle_gradient( x0 , " y0" , " r0" , " g0" , " b0" ", ..." )
Rasterize a triangle with independently specified per-vertex colors,
linearly interpolated (Gouraud-style) across the triangle's interior.
.TP
.BI fill_triangle_z( x0 , " y0" , " z0" ", ..." , " r" , " g" , " b" )
Rasterize a flat-shaded triangle with per-pixel depth testing against
the active z-buffer. Each vertex carries a floating-point depth
.RI ( z );
a pixel is drawn only when it is nearer (smaller
.IR z )
than the value already stored in the depth buffer.
.TP
.BI fill_triangle_affine( x0 , " y0" , " u0" , " v0" ", ..." , " tex_ptr" , " tex_w" , " tex_h" )
PS1-style affine texture-mapped triangle. UV coordinates are linearly
interpolated without perspective correction. The texture must be in
RGB565 format (2 bytes per pixel, RRRRRGGG GGGBBBBB).
.TP
.BI fill_triangle_persp( x0 , " y0" , " z0" , " u0" , " v0" ", ..." , " tex_ptr" , " tex_w" , " tex_h" )
PS2-style perspective-correct texture-mapped triangle. Interpolates 1/z,
u/z, v/z and divides to recover true UV coordinates, eliminating texture
warping on angled surfaces. The inner loop corrects perspective every 8
pixels and interpolates UV affinely between (classic PS2 subdivision,
~20x fewer divisions), writing each pixel as a single 32-bit BGRA store.
.TP
.BI fill_triangle_pcolor( verts , " tex_ptr" , " tex_w" , " tex_h" )
Perspective-correct textured triangle with per-vertex colors. The
.I verts
parameter points to 24 int64 values (3 vertices x 8 values: x,y,z,u,v,r,g,b).
Texture color is multiplied by interpolated vertex color.
.TP
.B zbuffer.clear()
Reset the depth buffer to a far value prior to rendering a frame.
.TP
.B time.now_us()
Microseconds via QueryPerformanceCounter/QueryPerformanceFrequency;
high-resolution timing for benchmarks and precise frame timing.
.TP
.B time.now_ms()
Returns milliseconds elapsed since system start, for frame timing and
FPS measurement.
.SS CPU topology
At startup the runtime calls
.B GetLogicalProcessorInformation
and populates a set of read-only globals accessible via the
.B cpu.*
builtins:
.TP
.B cpu.physical_cores()
Number of physical processor cores as reported by the OS.
.TP
.B cpu.logical_cores()
Total number of logical processors (hardware threads), equal to
physical cores times threads-per-core when SMT is active.
.TP
.B cpu.threads_per_core()
Logical cores divided by physical cores. 2 when SMT/Hyper-Threading
is active, 1 otherwise.
.TP
.B cpu.safe_thread_limit()
.BR cpu.logical_cores() \ \-\ 1,
with a minimum of 1. A conservative upper bound for the number of
worker threads to spawn so that one logical core is left free for the
OS and the window thread.
.TP
.B cpu.hyperthreaded()
Returns 1 if SMT (Intel Hyper-Threading or AMD SMT) is detected on at
least one physical core, 0 otherwise. Detected via the
.B ProcessorCore.Flags
field of
.BR SYSTEM_LOGICAL_PROCESSOR_INFORMATION .
If
.B GetLogicalProcessorInformation
fails, all
.B cpu.*
values fall back to 1 and
.B cpu.hyperthreaded()
returns 0.
.TP
.B cpu.simd_detect()
Re-runs CPUID/XGETBV SIMD feature detection (also run automatically at
startup); idempotent, returns 1.
.TP
.BR cpu.has_sse() ", " cpu.has_sse2() ", " cpu.has_sse3() ", " cpu.has_ssse3() ", " cpu.has_sse41() ", " cpu.has_sse42() ", " cpu.has_fma() ", " cpu.has_avx() ", " cpu.has_avx2() ", " cpu.has_avx512f()
Return 1 if the named instruction-set extension is present, else 0. The
AVX, AVX2, and AVX\-512F predicates additionally require OS\-enabled
register state (OSXSAVE plus XCR0), so they return 0 when the CPU
supports the ISA but the OS has not enabled it.
.SS Concurrency
.B "thread { ... }"
spawns a Win32 thread running the block body; the body is compiled to a
standalone thread procedure and launched with
.BR CreateThread .
Multiple thread blocks may be spawned before a sync (up to 64 outstanding).
.PP
.B "sync { ... }"
waits for all threads spawned since the last sync using
.BR WaitForMultipleObjects ,
closes their handles, and resets the handle table. Statements inside the
sync body run after the wait completes.
.PP
.B "lock { ... }"
provides mutual exclusion via a single global
.B CRITICAL_SECTION
initialized at startup, bracketing the body with
.B EnterCriticalSection
and
.BR LeaveCriticalSection .
Only one thread runs inside any lock block at a time; the section is
reentrant on the owning thread.
.SS Memory and buffers
Raw heap buffers, addressed by plain-integer pointers. Accessors are unchecked and inlined to a single machine instruction at
the call site (no function-call overhead); bounds are the programmer's
responsibility.
.TP
.B mem.alloc(nbytes)
Allocate zero-initialized heap memory; returns the buffer address as an
integer, or 0 on failure.
.TP
.B mem.free(ptr)
Free a buffer obtained from mem.alloc.
.TP
.BR mem.poke8(ptr,byteoff,val) ", " mem.peek8(ptr,byteoff)
Store / load a single byte at a byte offset.
.TP
.BR mem.poke64(ptr,byteoff,val) ", " mem.peek64(ptr,byteoff)
Store / load 8 bytes at a byte offset.
.TP
.BI mem.pokef32( ptr , " byteoff" , " floatval" )
Store a 32-bit float at a byte offset (narrowed from Slag's 64-bit
double). Lets SIMD vec4 buffers be filled with readable float literals
instead of hand-packed IEEE-754 bit patterns.
.SS Bit manipulation
.TP
.B bit.shl(value,count)
Left shift. Inlined to a single shl instruction; enables 16.16 fixed-point
arithmetic (e.g., bit.shl(n, 16) converts an integer to fixed-point).
.TP
.B bit.shr(value,count)
Unsigned right shift. Inlined to a single shr instruction; bit.shr(fixed, 16)
converts fixed-point back to integer.
.SS Matrix stack
A 3x4 transformation matrix stack using 16.16 fixed-point arithmetic.
Pre-computed sin/cos lookup tables enable fast rotation. All coordinates
use fixed-point format: convert with bit.shl(n, 16), convert back with
bit.shr(result, 16).
.TP
.B mat.identity()
Reset current matrix to identity.
.TP
.BR mat.push() ", " mat.pop()
Push current matrix onto stack (16 levels max) / pop from stack.
.TP
.B mat.translate(x,y,z)
Multiply translation into current matrix.
.TP
.B mat.scale(sx,sy,sz)
Multiply scale into current matrix.
.TP
.BR mat.rotate_x(angle) ", " mat.rotate_y(angle) ", " mat.rotate_z(angle)
Multiply rotation into current matrix. Angle 0-255 maps to 0-360 degrees.
.TP
.BR mat.transform_x(x,y,z) ", " mat.transform_y(...) ", " mat.transform_z(...)
Transform a point by the current matrix, returning a single coordinate.
.SS SIMD (SSE2)
128-bit vector operations for graphics and bulk processing. All pointer
arguments are 16-byte buffers (from mem.alloc).
.TP
.BR simd.addf4(d,a,b) ", " simd.subf4 ", " simd.mulf4 ", " simd.divf4
Packed 4-float arithmetic operations.
.TP
.B simd.dot4(d,a,b)
Dot product of two vec4s; result broadcast to all 4 elements.
.TP
.B simd.cross3(d,a,b)
3D cross product (w component = 0).
.TP
.B simd.normalize4(d,v)
Normalize a vec4 to unit length.
.TP
.B simd.lint4(d,a,b,t)
Linear interpolation: a + t*(b-a).
.TP
.B simd.mat4_mul(d,a,b)
4x4 matrix multiply (row-major).
.TP
.B simd.mat4_vec4(d,m,v)
Matrix-vector multiply.
.TP
.B simd.rgb565_unpack(r,g,b,pixels)
Extract R/G/B channels from 8 RGB565 pixels.
.TP
.B simd.rgb565_pack(d,r,g,b)
Pack R/G/B channels to 8 RGB565 pixels.
.TP
.B simd.rgb565_blend(d,a,b,alpha)
Alpha blend 8 RGB565 pixels (alpha: 8x16-bit values, 0-256 range).
.SS BMP and mesh management
BMP image loading and mesh management for 3D geometry.
.TP
.BR mesh.bmp_width(ptr) ", " mesh.bmp_height(ptr)
Return dimensions of a 24-bit uncompressed BMP loaded via readfile().
.TP
.B mesh.bmp_pixel(ptr,x,y)
Return 0x00RRGGBB for the pixel at (x,y).
.TP
.B mesh.bmp_gray(ptr,x,y)
Return grayscale value 0-255 for the pixel at (x,y).
.TP
.B mesh.create(verts,faces)
Allocate a mesh with capacity for N vertices and M faces; returns handle.
.TP
.B mesh.destroy(handle)
Free mesh memory.
.TP
.BR mesh.set_vertex(h,i,x,y,z) ", " mesh.get_vertex_x(h,i) ", etc."
Set or get vertex coordinates (16.16 fixed-point).
.TP
.BR mesh.set_face(h,i,v0,v1,v2) ", " mesh.get_face(h,i,c)
Set or get face vertex indices (c=0/1/2).
.TP
.B mesh.from_heightmap(bmp_ptr,scale_xz,scale_y)
Generate terrain mesh from grayscale BMP.
.TP
.BR mesh.vertex_count(h) ", " mesh.face_count(h)
Query mesh size.
.SS Procedural textures
Generate procedural texture values (0-255 grayscale).
.TP
.B tex.checker(x,y,size)
Returns 0 or 255 in a checkerboard pattern.
.TP
.BR tex.gradient_h(x,width) ", " tex.gradient_v(y,height)
Linear gradient from 0 to 255.
.TP
.B tex.brick(x,y,bw,bh,mortar)
Brick pattern (0=mortar, 255=brick).
.TP
.B tex.noise2d(x,y,seed)
Hash-based noise, returns 0-255.
.TP
.B tex.perlin2d(x,y,freq,seed)
Perlin noise, returns 0-255.
.TP
.BR tex.wood(x,y,rings,seed) ", " tex.marble(x,y,freq,seed)
Organic patterns (wood grain, marble veins).
.SS Networking
TCP networking via ws2_32; supports persistent peer-to-peer sessions
between two machines running the same program. Programs using networking
must link
.B ws2_32
.RB ( \-lws2_32 ).
.TP
.BR net.start() ", " net.end()
Begin a networking session (WSAStartup) / close sockets and clean up.
.TP
.B net.bind(port)
Create a socket, bind, and listen on a port (does not block).
.TP
.B net.accept()
Block until a peer connects to the bound socket; call in a loop for a
persistent listener.
.TP
.B net.listen(port)
Convenience call: bind, listen, and accept in one blocking step.
.TP
.B net.connect(host, port)
Connect to a peer; host is a string literal such as "127.0.0.1".
.TP
.BR net.send(byte) ", " net.recv()
Send / receive a single byte (recv returns an int, \-1 on failure).
.TP
.B net.send_buf(ptr, len)
Send len bytes from a buffer, looping until all are sent.
.TP
.B net.recv_buf(ptr, maxlen)
Receive up to maxlen bytes into a buffer; returns the count (0 when the
peer closes). A single recv may return fewer bytes than requested.
.TP
.B net.ack()
Returns 1/0: did the last network operation succeed.
.TP
.B net.connected()
Returns 1/0: is the active connection still alive (clears on disconnect).
.SS Input event handlers
Event handlers are declared with the
.B on
keyword inside a function body and are dispatched directly from the
window procedure:
.PP
.RS
.nf
on key_down(int key) { ... }
on key_up(int key) { ... }
on mouse_move(int x, int y) { ... }
on mouse_down(int button) { ... }   // 0=left, 1=right, 2=middle
on mouse_up(int button) { ... }
on mouse_wheel(int delta) { ... }   // delta is +-120 per notch
.fi
.RE
.PP
Handlers not declared by the program default to no-op stubs.
.SS Shared input state
Because event handlers execute in their own stack frames, separate
from the main loop, a small set of accessor builtins is provided so
handlers and the main loop can communicate:
.PP
.RS
.nf
input.drag_x() / input.drag_y()
input.add_drag(dx, dy)
input.is_dragging() / input.set_dragging(v)
input.last_x() / input.last_y() / input.set_last(x, y)
input.wheel()           // returns and resets accumulated wheel delta
input.add_wheel(delta)
input.set_bbox(minx, miny, maxx, maxy)
input.in_bbox(mx, my)   // axis-aligned hit test
.fi
.RE
.SH NOT YET IMPLEMENTED
The following are described in the language design but are not
currently functional:
.IP \(bu 2
Dynamic arrays
.IP \(bu 2
Encrypted peer-to-peer via Windows CNG (bcrypt) Diffie\-Hellman key
exchange and AES (planned; the networking and memory primitives it
depends on are in place)
.IP \(bu 2
A self-hosting compiler
.RS
.nf
cd compiler
gcc -Wall -Wextra -o slag main.c lexer.c ast.c parser.c codegen.c \e
    window_runtime.c net_runtime.c mem_runtime.c matrix_runtime.c \e
    simd_runtime.c mesh_runtime.c texture_runtime.c
.fi
.RE
.SS Compiling and running a Slag program
.RS
.nf
./slag program.slag
nasm -f win64 program.asm -o program.obj
x86_64-w64-mingw32-gcc program.obj -o program.exe \e
    -nostdlib -lkernel32 -luser32 -lgdi32 -lws2_32 -e _start
.fi
.RE
.PP
Add
.B \-mwindows
to suppress the console window for GUI-only programs.
.SS A minimal windowed program
.RS
.nf
function main() {
    window.open(320, 240, "Slag Demo");

    on key_down(int key) {
        if (key == 27) {        // Escape
            window.close();
        }
    }

    while (window.is_open()) {
        fill_triangle(40, 40, 200, 60, 90, 200, 255, 60, 60);
        window.flush();
    }

    return;
}
.fi
.RE
.SS Querying CPU topology
.RS
.nf
function main() {
    println(cpu.physical_cores());
    println(cpu.logical_cores());
    println(cpu.threads_per_core());
    println(cpu.hyperthreaded());
    return;
}
.fi
.RE
.SH FILES
.TP
.I *.slag
Slag source files.
.TP
.I *.asm
NASM x86-64 Win64 assembly emitted by the compiler.
